a great example of an app

00:54:10.846 --> 00:54:16.586
that takes advantage of iOS and
OS X, Handoff, iCloud and more

00:54:16.586 --> 00:54:18.536
to deliver an optimized
experience

00:54:18.536 --> 00:54:19.836
on each of these platforms.

00:54:20.216 --> 00:54:22.626
We talked about this new
opportunity of four platforms,

00:54:22.626 --> 00:54:24.456
and this is an app
that does a great job

00:54:24.456 --> 00:54:25.936
of heading in that direction.

00:54:26.166 --> 00:54:26.946
Congratulations.

00:54:27.506 --> 00:54:30.546
All right, our last
winner today is an app

00:54:30.546 --> 00:54:32.376
that is incredibly
state-of-the-art

00:54:32.446 --> 00:54:34.506
and incredibly accessible.

00:54:35.216 --> 00:54:38.976
It is djay Pro by
Algoriddim from Germany.

00:54:39.516 --> 00:54:49.576
[ Applause ]

00:54:50.076 --> 00:54:51.656
You've been here before.

00:54:51.656 --> 00:54:52.556
You've been here before, sir.

00:54:53.976 --> 00:54:55.626
Good. Congratulations.

00:54:56.516 --> 00:55:02.596
[ Music ]

00:55:03.096 --> 00:55:04.796
All right, so djay Pro is one

00:55:04.796 --> 00:55:09.206
of the first professional-grade
apps to fully leverage the audio

00:55:09.206 --> 00:55:11.676
and video capabilities
of the new iPad Pro.

00:55:12.166 --> 00:55:15.936
And these guys already won an
Apple Design Award in 2011,

00:55:16.226 --> 00:55:18.416
but they have done
so much since then

00:55:18.416 --> 00:55:20.356
and they continue to innovate.

00:55:20.536 --> 00:55:23.276
And they have consistently
stayed in lockstep

00:55:23.336 --> 00:55:25.976
with us every time
we released a new OS,

00:55:25.976 --> 00:55:28.506
every time there's
some new technology,

00:55:28.736 --> 00:55:32.166
and every time there's
a new device to support.

00:55:32.166 --> 00:55:33.086
Really impressive.

00:55:33.466 --> 00:55:36.586
And we love this app because
it sets new benchmarks

00:55:36.586 --> 00:55:40.616
for performance, for features,
for use of Apple technology,

00:55:40.926 --> 00:55:45.096
for multi-device support,
and for accessibility.

00:55:45.186 --> 00:55:49.186
And I'd like to ask Ryan
to show the app off now.

00:55:50.026 --> 00:55:50.936
>> Hey. Thanks, John.

00:55:51.096 --> 00:55:52.186
My name is Ryan Dour.

00:55:52.186 --> 00:55:54.246
I'm an engineer on the
Accessibility Team here

00:55:54.246 --> 00:55:56.166
at Apple, but I'm also a deejay.

00:55:56.506 --> 00:55:58.376
All of my life, I've
been visually impaired.

00:55:58.376 --> 00:56:00.156
But during high school
and college,

00:56:00.156 --> 00:56:02.486
I lost most of my
remaining usable vision.

00:56:03.076 --> 00:56:05.166
I've always deejayed with
CD players and mixers

00:56:05.196 --> 00:56:07.526
because they offer a
hands-on tactile experience.

00:56:08.146 --> 00:56:10.136
However, with the rise
of digital deejaying,

00:56:10.136 --> 00:56:11.646
I was feeling pretty left out.

00:56:12.676 --> 00:56:15.596
About a year ago, I got my
hands on djay Pro for the Mac

00:56:15.596 --> 00:56:17.866
and this external deejay
controller and I got back

00:56:17.866 --> 00:56:19.736
into it, and it's been
a great time since.

00:56:19.736 --> 00:56:25.816
However, djay Pro for iPad
takes accessible deejaying

00:56:25.816 --> 00:56:28.266
to a whole new level, and I'd
love to show it to you now.

00:56:29.026 --> 00:56:33.376
So, over here, I have an
iPad Pro running djay Pro

00:56:33.576 --> 00:56:34.796
and this external mixer.

00:56:34.846 --> 00:56:37.036
I'm going to go ahead and
throw on my headphones now.

00:56:37.906 --> 00:56:41.206
So, here's the thing
that's interesting.

00:56:41.206 --> 00:56:42.746
The external deejay
controller acts

00:56:42.746 --> 00:56:44.516
as an extension of
the onscreen UI.

00:56:45.526 --> 00:56:48.526
And so I can use it
to really create kind

00:56:48.526 --> 00:56:49.856
of a pretty cool performance.

00:56:49.916 --> 00:56:53.226
Also, you're probably wondering
what of this can I see.

00:56:53.226 --> 00:56:56.426
Not much. I pretty much can see
the light coming from the screen

00:56:56.426 --> 00:56:58.406
and some of the, you know,
colorful lights coming

00:56:58.406 --> 00:57:00.926
from the deejay controller,
but that's about it.

00:57:00.926 --> 00:57:03.066
So knowing that, we're
going to use VoiceOver

00:57:03.066 --> 00:57:04.106
to control this interface.

00:57:04.106 --> 00:57:10.006
Let's go ahead and
get the music started.

00:57:10.296 --> 00:57:12.756
OK, so the first thing
I'd like to point out is

00:57:12.756 --> 00:57:13.596
that I have access

00:57:13.596 --> 00:57:15.036
to information I've
never had before.

00:57:15.036 --> 00:57:16.556
For example, the time.

00:57:16.556 --> 00:57:18.266
How much time is
left on this track?

00:57:18.266 --> 00:57:21.146
Let's find out.

00:57:21.146 --> 00:57:21.936
That's perfect.

00:57:21.936 --> 00:57:24.226
OK. So I'm the deejay, I'm
supposed to keep the music going

00:57:24.226 --> 00:57:25.746
and now I have that
kind of information.

00:57:26.056 --> 00:57:27.946
I also can use these
tempo sliders.

00:57:28.236 --> 00:57:33.316
For example, if I touch it
right now -- hold on a second.

00:57:34.256 --> 00:57:36.176
So we hear it's at a
standard playback speed.

00:57:36.176 --> 00:57:38.296
But if I slow it down
using the deejay controller

00:57:38.296 --> 00:57:43.626
and I touch it again,

00:57:44.666 --> 00:57:47.456
we can hear exactly how far
I slowed that track down.

00:57:47.456 --> 00:57:48.206
That's really cool.

00:57:48.686 --> 00:57:51.136
I also can use these
multidimensional effects pads.

00:57:51.196 --> 00:57:52.846
For example, if I touch
it the first time --

00:57:53.736 --> 00:57:55.806
but the second time.

00:58:01.176 --> 00:58:02.176
Really cool stuff, right?

00:58:02.246 --> 00:58:06.016
So between these effects
pads, this external controller

00:58:06.016 --> 00:58:07.266
and all this accessible UI,

00:58:07.266 --> 00:58:08.886
I can do a pretty
cool performance.

00:58:08.886 --> 00:58:10.566
So I'd like to go ahead
and ask the stage here

00:58:10.566 --> 00:58:13.776
to please take VoiceOver
off of the PA systems --

00:58:13.776 --> 00:58:15.566
that it's only available
to me and my headphones.

00:58:17.746 --> 00:58:18.746
Cool. Thank you very much.

00:58:18.746 --> 00:58:19.916
And I'm going to
mix for you now.

00:58:20.296 --> 00:58:20.826
Here we go.

00:58:21.516 --> 00:58:44.516
[ Music ]

00:58:45.516 --> 00:58:56.516
[ Applause ]

00:58:57.516 --> 00:59:11.756
[ Music ]

00:59:12.256 --> 00:59:13.856
So that's djay Pro
from Algoriddim.

00:59:14.516 --> 00:59:23.716
[ Applause ]

00:59:24.216 --> 00:59:25.166
>> Ryan, you're the man.

00:59:25.446 --> 00:59:26.306
>> I've got to tell you --

00:59:26.426 --> 00:59:29.286
this is an incredible
custom user interface.

00:59:29.666 --> 00:59:33.196
They did not use UIKit
with this interface at all.

00:59:33.196 --> 00:59:35.456
They didn't get any of their
accessibility for free.

00:59:35.866 --> 00:59:38.566
Considering that,
their implementation

00:59:38.676 --> 00:59:43.046
of our accessibility APIs is
nothing less than spectacular.

00:59:43.046 --> 00:59:44.796
So I want to let everybody know,

00:59:44.796 --> 00:59:46.956
and especially all the
visually-impaired deejays

00:59:46.956 --> 00:59:50.946
out there, this app has
really enriched my life.

00:59:50.946 --> 00:59:53.986
So I absolutely cannot
wait to see what the rest

00:59:53.986 --> 00:59:55.796
of you developers
make accessible next!

00:59:55.796 --> 00:59:57.576
Thank you so much, John!

00:59:58.236 --> 00:59:58.946
>> Yeah. Good job.

00:59:59.516 --> 01:00:04.576
[ Applause ]

01:00:05.076 --> 01:00:08.396
Ryan, you're the man.

01:00:08.396 --> 01:00:15.126
djay Pro -- a beautiful, fully
accessible, super sophisticated,

01:00:15.246 --> 01:00:18.776
high-performance app
built for iOS and OS X.

01:00:19.366 --> 01:00:20.346
Congratulations, guys.

